Draft Resolution Language  
( calibrated to assert a clear legal position without overstating the certainty of every subsidiary question )

The [Senate / House / Parliament / Council / Board]—

1. Recalls that the 1982 United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea (UNCLOS) sets forth the exclusive legal framework for the maritime entitlements of coastal States;  

2. Notes that on 12 July 2016 an Arbitral Tribunal constituted under Annex VII of UNCLOS, in the matter of Philippines v. China, rendered a final and binding award that:  
   a. found that historic-rights claims within the ‘nine-dash line’ exceeding the territorial sea, exclusive economic zone and continental-shelf limits generated by land features are “without lawful effect” under UNCLOS; and  
   b. concluded that no feature in the Spratly archipelago is capable, either individually or collectively, of generating an exclusive economic zone or continental shelf;  

3. Affirms that the Tribunal’s decision is final, not subject to appeal, and creates binding obligations between the parties to the dispute under international law;  

4. Reiterates that, in the view of this body, the People’s Republic of China’s continuing assertion of ‘historic rights’ to resources across the vast expanse of the South China Sea enclosed by the nine-dash line is incompatible with the Convention and therefore has no basis in international law as reflected in UNCLOS;  

5. Urges all claimants to base any maritime claims solely on the rules-based order established by UNCLOS and to respect the Tribunal’s award;  

6. Calls upon the Executive to continue diplomatic, legal and, where appropriate, multilateral efforts to uphold the Convention and the integrity of its dispute-settlement mechanisms.

Key drafting choices that avoid over-statement  
- “…incompatible with the Convention and therefore has no basis in international law as reflected in UNCLOS” (does not say “violates customary international law in every respect,” which would over-claim where the Tribunal itself was careful).  
- Grounds the condemnation in the specific, authoritative 2016 award rather than in an abstract assertion of universality.  
- Does not purport to settle questions the Tribunal did not decide (e.g., sovereignty over the islands themselves).
